18","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1305":"1305","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1367":"1367","1418":"1418","Abt 1328":"about 1328","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Madresfield, Worcestershire, England":"Madresfield, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Drayton Paslow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Drayton Parslow, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Parslow","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: Anglicized form of the Old French nickname <i>passe lewe</i> ‘cross the water’; see   Pashley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Parlow","meanings":["German: habitational name from any of several places so named in Brandenburg and Pomerania.","English: variant of   Parslow  , itself a variant of   Pashley  . Compare   Partlow  .","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Parlov</b>: possibly a nickname ultimately derived from Italian <i>parlare</i> ‘to speak’ (<i>parlati</i> in a colloquial Slavicized form)."]},{"name":"Pashley","meanings":["English:","nickname from Old French <i>passe lewe</i> ‘cross the water’, probably used for a seafarer or sailor. Compare   Parslow  . The name was sometimes treated like a Norman habitational name by adding the preposition <i>de</i>, although no such placename has been identified in Normandy or neighboring regions.","habitational name from Pashley in the parish of Ticehurst, Sussex. The placename is from Old English <i>Pæcces</i> + <i>lēah</i> ‘Pæcca's wood or clearing’. A district of Eastbourne, Sussex, bearing this name derives it from the surname; a family called Pashley had moved there from Ticehurst by the later part of the 13th century."]},{"name":"Passmore","meanings":["English (mainly Devon):","nickname from Old French <i>passe mer</i> ‘cross the sea’, used for a seafarer or sailor. See also   Parslow  .","habitational name from Peasemore (Berkshire). The placename derives from Old English <i>pise</i> ‘pea’ + <i>mere</i> ‘pool’."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ralph Parslow was born about 1328, in Drayton Parslow, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Nicholas Paslewe. He married Amye Kynaston in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1328–":"umbes 1328–Surnud","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1367–1379":"1367–1379","1369–1418":"1369–1418","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1305":"1305","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1367":"1367","1418":"1418","Abt 1328":"umbes 1328","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Madresfield, Worcestershire, England":"Madresfield, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Drayton Paslow, Buckinghamshire, England":"Drayton Parslow, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1328–":"noin 1328–Kuollut","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1329–Female":"1329–Kuollut","1367–1379":"1367–1379","1369–1418":"1369–1418","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1369":"1369","1379":"1379","1367":"1367","1418":"1418","Abt 1328":"noin 1328","1329":"1329","1328":"1328","Madresfield, Worcestershire, En